The official representative of the People’s Militia of the self-proclaimed Lugansk People’s Republic (LPR), Andrei Marochko, said that in the winter of 2018-2019 Ukraine will send at least 3,000 new recruits to the Donbass.
According to him, in this way, Kiev plans to “at least somehow complete the units”.
"The reluctance of Ukrainian citizens to serve in the ranks of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, mass layoffs led to low staffing of units," Marochko said, quoted by RIA Novosti.
He also did not rule out that the real numbers of Ukrainians drafted into the army can be increased if necessary.
In 2014-2017, Kiev launched the so-called anti-terrorist operation (ATO), which was later replaced by the Joint Forces Operation (JFO).
It was assumed that this measure will lead to the strengthening of the role of the Ukrainian security forces in the settlement of the situation.
At the end of August 2018, the situation in the Donbass escalated due to the murder of the head of the DPR Alexander Zakharchenko.
The DPR authorities qualified the incident as a terrorist attack.
During the investigation of the criminal case, several people involved in the explosion were detained.
According to preliminary data, they confirmed that the sabotage was organized by the Ukrainian special services.
U.S. forces Musk to step down as Tesla’s chairman
The American businessman Elon Musk will leave the post of chairman of the board of directors of the company founded by him Tesla at the request of the US authorities.
To settle the claims of the Federal Securities and Exchange Commission, the entrepreneur will also pay $20 million.
According to CNBC, the pre-trial agreement with the agency allows Musk to remain in the leading position at Tesla.
At the same time, he is obliged to pay $20 million and leave the post of Chairman of the Board of Directors within 45 days of the agreement and for at least three years.
Two independent directors will be appointed.
It is clarified that the agreement still needs to be approved by the court.
On September 28, it became known that the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission accused Musk of misleading shareholders by stating that there were sufficient funds to buy back the company’s shares and filed a lawsuit against the entrepreneur.
The businessman tweeted that he wanted to buy Tesla shares for $420 per share, but never did.
After the tweet, the company's shares grew by almost 11%.
The head of the British foreign Ministry compared the EU with the Soviet Union and prison
British Foreign Secretary Jeremy Hunt compared the European Union to the Soviet Union and accused Brussels of capturing member states of the community.
This statement was made by the diplomat at the congress of the ruling Conservative Party in Birmingham, which opened on Sunday, September 30.
As noted by the Daily Mail, Hunt thus commented on the difficulties in the Brexit negotiation process.
What happened to the belief in the European dream and its ideals?
The EU was created to protect freedom, and the Soviet Union did not allow anyone to leave it.
The lesson of history is clear: if you turn the EU from a community into a prison, the desire to leave it will not decrease, but only grow, and we will not be the only prisoner who wants to escape from captivity.
He also added that attempts to punish Britain for the decision to leave the European Union will only exacerbate the crisis, notes Gazeta.ru.
In mid-September, British Prime Minister Theresa May said Brexit talks were at a standstill.
She commented on the results of the informal EU summit in Salzburg.
The decision on Brexit was made in 2016 following a referendum.
The withdrawal of the United Kingdom is expected to take place before April 2019, but negotiations with Brussels on this issue are complicated by many factors.
In particular, there is still no clear agreement on how the parties will interact after London leaves the community.
The issue of the Irish border is also open.
