Elon Musk is forced to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their dispute over the fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the TV channel, as part of the agreements, Musk will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the post of head of Tesla.
The founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
A similar amount will be collected from Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur, included in the list of the 50 richest people on the planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of space corporation SpaceX, neurotechnical company Neuralink and the developer of electric cars Tesla, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about a possible buyout.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The $420 share was reportedly set “because of the importance of this number in marijuana culture,” Bloomberg reported earlier, citing co-director of the commission’s security department, Stephen Pekin.
Elon Musk later abandoned his plans to buy back the shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considers the allegations of fraud unfounded, and added that he is very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I did not violate it in any way,” the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
At the same time, in August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a collective lawsuit against Musk, complaining about the financial losses suffered.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman’s posts brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the businessman's tweets were misleading, which forced sellers of Tesla shares to buy papers at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that the reckless statements of Elon Musk led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk was accused of stock exchange fraud and the head of the research company Citron Research.
Meanwhile, if Musk had not been able to settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would have been threatened with dismissal and even imprisonment.
This, in particular, said CNBC, the former chairman of the commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is a “good guy who doesn’t know how to run a car company.”
