In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 inmates have escaped from a prison in Indonesia’s central Sulawesi province.
The escape was possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island of magnitude 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when prisoners in the prison of the city of Palu demanded their release in connection with the tremors.
More than 340 prisoners staged a riot and set fire to the facility.
The police, who arrived at the scene of the emergency, partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from the prison.
The building itself was seriously damaged, and the guards had difficulty keeping the prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi, increased to 832 people.
As a result, transport, electricity and communications to some areas of the island have not yet been established.
