A few years earlier, being cold, he sowed mucus from his own nose on a Petri cup (this is a glass cap in which experiments are conducted with bacteria) and a few days later found that the bacteria there were destroyed.
They were also found to have penicillin.
Fleming’s name was included in the list of the 100 most outstanding personalities in human history.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases, previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, Fleming came to the French capital in 1945, the Paris newspapers wrote: “To defeat fascism and liberate France, he did more than dozens of divisions.”
According to experts, Fleming's discovery of the world's first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people on Earth.
Alexander Fleming died of a heart attack at his home in London in 1955.
