Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia was almost absent in a negative way
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly to be successful for Russia and does not exclude that it will be a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global problems.
“The uniqueness of this 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric to which we have almost become accustomed in recent years in relation to Russia has now been much more muted,” the senator said in an interview published Sunday by the Russian newspaper.
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes “designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this series, at least in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which spoke unanimously on this issue.”
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "the topic of Russia was practically absent in a negative way."
“If we carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least, the choir was not quite accurate,” the politician noted, noting that Russia “was no longer some kind of wall, which is trained by the tennis ball”.
The head of the profile committee of the Soviet Federation does not exclude that this indicates a trend that, in his opinion, "will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, in two, in three."
"I do not exclude that the current session in some sense can be a turning point," Kosachev admitted, explaining that "too many examples of how with Russia's integration it is possible to move forward in international affairs."
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine yet, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," he added.
This is due to the fact that he believes that there is an "adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just a possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of our time".
“I don’t want to make a mistake, but I have a feeling that we are somewhere passing a point where the movement will no longer be a backward movement, it will be a forward movement,” he added.
Another “interesting and important feeling” in this context, Kosachev called “a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop.”
"I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of the Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergey Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, in large part, no one was interested, the situation is different.
According to him, this is due to the fact that “the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, does not have answers to the questions of how to solve the world’s problems due to the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, the lack of ideas about how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problems of migration.”
"And here the request for a Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," Kosachev said, stressing that he believes in this sense "this session is successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
