The AfD became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” is breaking another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel’s ratings are falling.
Apparently, the inhabitants of Germany began to get seriously tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country has become a desirable target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The latest polls show that the anti-immigrant party Alternative for Germany is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, climbing to the second place in the ranking of popular sympathies.
Right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one percentage point gap can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is impossible not to mention the fact that the AfD, created in 2013 from a small group of eurosceptic economists, managed to turn into a serious political force.
The CSU/CDU ruling bloc, which has about 30 per cent, continues to hold the lead in the overall standings.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
The Social Democrats were followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
The Evolution of "Alternatives"
The Alternative for Germany party was formed in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s policy, but at first it dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and cooperation within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany’s “sponsorship” of the weak economies of the EU, did not exclude the possibility of returning to the German mark and the country’s complete withdrawal from the European Union.
Against the backdrop of the deepening immigration crisis, the AfD’s political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party, which occupied a niche of eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of “Alternatives for Germany” received seats in the European Parliament.
